      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nWhen we began our studies on multiplication tables, we observed that it is possible—with the help of squared paper—to represent the tables graphically, creating shapes such as lines and triangles",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b6428e19-afcf-4d3b-916d-46e5a332ef53",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "In this text, we will deepen our understanding of triangles and explore their relationship with two other multiplication tables.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_triangle",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Triangle\n\nBefore proceeding, to further clarify the concepts introduced earlier and what we will explore next, we have filled the lower triangle formed by the connected points of the multiplication table of one",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b6428e19-afcf-4d3b-916d-46e5a332ef53",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ":"
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><canvas aria-label=\"chart\" id=\"chart1\" class=\"htChart\" style=\"width:30em !important; height:20em !important;\"></canvas></p><p class=\"desc\">Chart 1: Points of the multiplication table connected, forming a straight line <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('b77ec8fc-c988-45f3-82f8-03b136bf1aa9'); return false;\">Chart JS</a>.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Now, observing Chart 1, consider the following:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ":"
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: Defining the Triangle</b><br /><br />Looking at Chart 1, where the triangular area is highlighted, how would you describe this shape?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Compare your definition with a simplified version of the one provided by Eric W. Weisstein",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "f33dbf7c-924c-453f-bee5-a19388e75109",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W., Triangle",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ":"
            },
            {
               "text": "<ul class=\"citation\"><li><i>\"A triangle is a closed shape with three sides and three angles (formed by the intersection of its sides)...\"</i></li> </ul>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Beyond this general definition, Weisstein notes that the right triangle shown in the chart has specific components with distinct names. In Chart 2, we identify these elements and label them",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "f33dbf7c-924c-453f-bee5-a19388e75109",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W., Triangle",
                     "date_time": null
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "56edda64-d96e-4106-b1f8-676a235b818c",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W., Right Triangle",
                     "date_time": null
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ":"
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"imgcenter\"><svg height=\"245\" width=\"450\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\"><path d=\"M425 5 L75 200 L425 200 Z\" style=\"fill:none;stroke:green;stroke-width:3\" /><rect x=\"404\" y=\"179\" width=\"20\" height=\"20\" stroke=\"green\" fill=\"none\" stroke-width=\"3\" /><text x=\"125\" y=\"192\" font-size=\"1.5em\">α</text><text x=\"401\" y=\"45\" font-size=\"1.5em\">β</text><text x=\"235\" y=\"95\" font-size=\"2.5em\">c</text><text x=\"428\" y=\"120\" font-size=\"2.5em\">b</text><text x=\"265\" y=\"230\" font-size=\"2.5em\">a</text></svg></p><p class=\"desc\">Chart 2: Right triangle with its components labeled.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "- **a**, **b** and **c**: The sides of the triangle. Sides **a** and **b** are called **legs**, while **c** is the **hypotenuse**.\n- **α**, **β**, and <i class=\"fa-regular fa-square\"></i>: The angles formed by the intersection of the sides. The square symbol ( <i class=\"fa-regular fa-square\"></i> ) marking the angle between the horizontal and vertical sides is called the **right angle**.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_general_formula",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### A General Formula\n\nIn the multiplication table, we multiply different numbers **N** by a fixed value, obtaining their products. In the first text, we performed these operations and concluded that the following formulas exist for the multiplication tables of zero and one",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b6428e19-afcf-4d3b-916d-46e5a332ef53",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ":"
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math><mi>0</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>0</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>N</mi> </math></center></p><p><center><math><mi>N</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>1</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>N</mi> </math></center></p><p class=\"desc\">Forrmula 1: Formulas used in the multiplication tables of zero and one.</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b6428e19-afcf-4d3b-916d-46e5a332ef53",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": " "
            },
            {
               "text": "These two formulas can be expressed more generally",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "79d126c9-39ac-4679-904b-4ab69558e44e",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ":"
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math><mi>r</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>a</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>n</mi> </math></center></p><p class=\"desc\">Formula 2: General formula for multiplication tables.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "istable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "postmention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "In this formula:\n- *r*: is the product of the multiplication.\n *N*: is the factor representing the counted number.\n- *a*: in addition to being a multiplication factor, it receives different names in various contexts. However, regardless of its name, its function in multiplication remains the same: to modify a point's position relative to the horizontal line. For this reason, one of its names is **slope coefficient** (or **angular coefficient**).",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "istable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "postmention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 2: The Factor *a*</b><br /><br />When **a = 0**, the results become points aligned along the horizontal axis.<br />Cuando a = 1, the results form points along the diagonal, dividing the grid paper into two equal triangles.<br /><br />What would you expect to happen when <b>a</b> takes the values 2 and 3</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_two",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Multiply by Two (2)\n\nWhen we began studying this section, First Steps, the first subject related to the human body that we examined was symmetry—the existence of two sides that mirror each other",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "20b14681-88c0-438a-a273-a0902ae5db38",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team, Our Sides Are Equal",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2023",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table class=\"book_navigation\"><tr><td>Left hand</td><td>Right hand</td></tr><tr><td><img id=\"imgLH\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgLH', '0%')\" src=\"images/Left_Hand.png\" class=\"imgcenter\"/></td><td><img id=\"imgRH\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgRH', '0%')\" src=\"images/Right_Hand.png\" class=\"imgcenter\"/></td></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\">Figure 1: Hands reprsentation. The source codes are available in project GitHub (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('240800f3-ede4-4deb-9d4e-915a3a03fa68'); return false;\">History Tracers Team, <span class=\"htdate\"></span>, Source code</a>)</td></tr></table></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "istable": false,
               "imgdesc": "The figure shows a person's two hands raised with all fingers extended.",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "postmention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Dr. Francisco Barriga Puente, in his studies on the Brazilian Indigenous numerical system, identified a binary system based on the numbers one (1) and two (2). To represent larger values, such as six (6), they used repeated sums:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "ceffba8a-43be-4de3-a5c8-27cdf81311b1",
                     "text": "Puente, Francisco Barriga, pp. 33",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2020",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ":"
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math><mi>2</mi> <mo>and</mo> <mi>2</mi> <mo>and</mo> <mi>2</mi> </math></center></p><p class=\"desc\">Representation of the number six in a binary Indigenous system.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "istable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "postmention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "These examples help us construct the table of two.#### Building the Table\n\nTo create the table of two (2), we apply Formula 2, assigning the factor **a** the value two (2), which gives the following results:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div style=\"border-radius: 30px; margin: auto; border-style= solid; background-color: lightblue; width: 30%; text-align: center\"><b>Table of 2</b><br /><br /><math><mi>0</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>2</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>0</mi> </math><br /><math><mi>2</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>2</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>1</mi> </math><br /> <math><mi>4</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>2</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>2</mi></math><br /> <math><mi>6</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>2</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>3</mi> </math><br /> <math><mi>8</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>2</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>4</mi> </math><br /> <math><mi>10</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>2</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>5</mi> </math><br /> <math><mi>12</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>2</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>6</mi> </math><br /> <math><mi>14</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>2</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>7</mi> </math><br /><math><mi>16</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>2</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>8</mi> </math><br /> <math><mi>18</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>2</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>9</mi> </math><br /> <math><mi>20</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>2</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>10</mi> </math></div></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": " "
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Graphical Representation\n\nThis time, instead of drawing points and connecting them in separate charts (as in previous methods), we will use the same chart, following the steps outlined earlier",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b6428e19-afcf-4d3b-916d-46e5a332ef53",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ":"
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><canvas aria-label=\"chart\" id=\"chart2\" class=\"htChart\" style=\"width:30em !important; height:20em !important;\"></canvas></p><p class=\"desc\">Chart 3: Points from the table of two connected, forming a straight line. Chart created using <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('b77ec8fc-c988-45f3-82f8-03b136bf1aa9'); return false;\">Chart JS</a>.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": " "
            },
            {
               "text": "When comparing **Chart 3** with **Chart 1**, the figures appear nearly identical. However, the differences become evident when we plot the tables of one and two together in a single chart:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><canvas aria-label=\"chart\" id=\"chart3\" class=\"htChart\" style=\"width:30em !important; height:20em !important;\"></canvas></p><p class=\"desc\">Chart 4: Points from the tables of one and two connected, forming two lines. Chart built using <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('b77ec8fc-c988-45f3-82f8-03b136bf1aa9'); return false;\">Chart JS</a>.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": " "
            },
            {
               "text": "In **Chart 4**, we observe that—in addition to dividing the squared paper—the values on the vertical axis are greater for the products multiplied by two. Furthermore, the distance from the horizontal axis increases, resulting in a steeper angle.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      }
   ],
   "exercise_v2": [
      {
         "question": "Um triângulo é uma figura fechada com três lados e três ângulos?",
         "yesNoAnswer": "Yes",
         "additionalInfo": "Esta é a definição de triângulo que estamos utilizando neste capítulo, mas ainda há mais informações que podemos adicionar a definção do triângulo que serão ensinadas adiante."
      },
      {
         "question": "Quando realizamos a multiplicação, temos dois fatores, com um deles representando o valor que contamos, enquanto o outro representa um afastamento da linha horizontal?",
         "yesNoAnswer": "Yes",
         "additionalInfo": "Neste texto, nomeamos o fator <b>a</> como sendo coeficiente angular, e vimos como ele atua no resultado, afastando-o da linha horizontal."
      }
   ],
